Church fire in Nantes, France: parish volunteers admit arson is usually kind and taciturn-Zhongxin.com
BEIJING, July 26 (Xinhua) According to foreign media reports, on July 18, the famous Cathedral of St. Peter and St. Paul, a religious and historical building treasure in Nantes, France, was severely damaged in a fire, and the big organ was completely destroyed.
On the 26th local time, the Nantes prosecutor announced that a parish volunteer in charge of security work in the cathedral had been charged with arson and destruction.
He has admitted that he started the fire in the church.
According to the report, local prosecutor senas said that the 39-year-old parish volunteer from Rwanda admitted that he set fire to three places in the cathedral at night.
The person's lawyer said that the arsonist now regrets doing such a thing.
This person entered France through asylum several years ago, and was sheltered in the parish where the fire happened, and was taken in in the church.
The prosecution pointed out that recently, he tried to renew his visa and was talking with the police station about it.
However, the church said it still couldn't believe that this kind-hearted, smiling but quiet believer would destroy the church he loved so much.
On the day of the fire on July 18th, the volunteer had been questioned and investigated by the police because of the illogical problems in the narrative, but he was later released.
The picture shows firefighters on the scene.
On the evening of 25th, the professional engineers in the laboratory of Paris Central Police Department obtained new evidence, and this person was arraigned again.
This time, the man admitted his arson.
According to reports, if convicted of arson, the suspect may face 10 years imprisonment and a fine of 150,000 euros.
According to reports, the fire caused serious losses to St. Pierre and St. Paul's Cathedral. The organ in the church was completely burned, and the stained glass windows behind the organ were also seriously damaged.
Brunet, the chief architect of French historic buildings, believes that it is conservatively estimated that the restoration of Nantes Cathedral will take at least three years.
