Poland will withdraw from the European treaty to prevent violence against women
Poland will take steps to withdraw from the European Treaty on the Prevention of Violence against Women next week, the Polish Ministry of Justice said Saturday.
Poland's right-wing government cabinet said that the treaty required schools to teach students about gender issues, trampling on the parents' rights.
Polish Minister of Justice Joblo held a press conference and said that his Ministry of Justice would ask the Ministry of Labor and Family to withdraw from the treaty on Monday.
That treaty is also known as Istanbul Convention.
Gioblo said, "The treaty contains some elements that we think are harmful to the ideological nature."
Poland's ruling Law and Justice Party and its ruling coalition partners have a close alliance with the Roman Catholic Church and advocate a conservative social agenda.
During his successful re-election campaign this month, Polish President Duda made hostility to gay rights one of the main topics.
On Friday, thousands of Poles (most of them women) held protests against their withdrawal from the Convention in Warsaw and other cities.
Lempat, one of the organizers of the protest, said in a protest March in Warsaw that "the purpose of withdrawing from the treaty is to legalize domestic violence".
Some protesters held banners with the words "Law and Justice Party is Women's Hell".
The Law and Justice Party has long complained about the Istanbul Convention.
Poland's former centrist government ratified the Convention in 2015.
The government of Law and Justice Party stated that the treaty does not respect religion and requires teaching liberal social policies in schools.
But up to now, the party has not decided to withdraw from the convention.
(According to the Reuters report)
