The Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) issued an emergency airworthiness directive on the 24th, requiring an emergency inspection of about 2,000 Boeing 737NG and 737Classic passenger aircraft registered in the United States, because the corrosion of the air check valves of these passenger aircraft may cause the engine to stop in the air.
According to the FAA, so far, it has received four reports of engine parking of 737NG and 737Classic passenger aircraft in the air, so it made an urgent inspection request. The inspection targets are passenger aircraft that have been parked continuously for 7 days or more and passenger aircraft that have flown less than 11 times since re-flying.
The FAA warned that if the 5th check valves of all two engines of the passenger plane are corroded, they may be stuck in the open position, resulting in the complete loss of power of the passenger plane and the inability to restart the engines.
The aviation regulator ordered that once the check valve is found to be corroded, the airline operator must replace this key component before the passenger plane is put into service again.
Boeing responded later that day, because the COVID-19 outbreak reduced travel demand, many passenger planes were sealed up or used less, and "check valves were more susceptible to corrosion".
Boeing also said that it has advised airline operators to inspect the passenger aircraft involved in the directive, and if problems are found, Boeing will provide assistance in overhauling and replacing check valves.
The Associated Press reported that the passenger planes of major US air carriers usually fly several times a day, but after the outbreak of the COVID-19 epidemic, a large number of passenger planes were grounded; With the slow growth of passenger travel demand recently, some passenger planes have been put into operation again.
The FAA has not released the details of four air parking reports.
Alaska Airlines disclosed one of the incidents later on the 24th.
The airline operator said in a statement that one of its passenger planes flew from Seattle, Washington to Austin, Texas on July 15th, when an engine suddenly turned off and the passenger plane finally made an emergency landing at Austin Airport.
Alaska Airlines said that it had replaced the engine of the passenger plane and inspected the engines of six passenger planes according to FAA instructions.
American Airlines, United Airlines and Southwest Airlines respectively said on the 24th that there was no engine flameout associated with air check valves in their passenger planes.
Four passenger planes owned by American Airlines will be inspected, and 28 passenger planes owned by United Airlines will be inspected.
Delta Air Lines said it would inspect its 20 passenger planes, but did not say whether there had been any engine flameout.
Many media reported that FAA's Emergency Airworthiness Directive is another impact on Boeing.
A Boeing 737MAX passenger plane of Indonesian Lion Air and Ethiopian Airlines crashed in October 2018 and March 2019 respectively, killing 346 people in total.
This series of passenger aircraft was subsequently grounded globally, which was discontinued in January this year and resumed production in May.
In June, FAA Director Steve Dixon admitted that the FAA "made a mistake" in the supervision of Boeing.
