Tibetan antelope in Hoh Xil enters the migration season-Xinhuanet
Xinhua News Agency, Xining, July 25 (Reporter Wang Jinjin) The reporter learned from Wudaoliang Protection Station, Hoh Xil Management Office, Yangtze River Source Park, Sanjiangyuan National Park Administration, that the monitoring showed that Tibetan antelopes who had migrated to Zhuonaihu Tibetan Antelope Aggregation area, the hinterland of Hoh Xil, were finishing giving birth one after another and began to bring their cubs back to their original habitat.
According to the monitoring picture near Wudaoliang Protection Station, on July 25th, about 40 female Tibetan antelopes led three young Tibetan antelopes to pass through the Beida Bridge of Wudaoliang on the Qinghai-Tibet Highway 3002 km in succession, and the Tibetan antelopes have started to move back.
According to expert analysis, in recent years, the number of Tibetan antelope cubs in the migrating sheep accounted for one fourth to one fifth of the total number of Tibetan antelopes.
Lian Xinming, an associate researcher at the Northwest Plateau Institute of Biology, Chinese Academy of Sciences, said: "In the early stage of migration, Tibetan antelopes faced a higher risk of being preyed, so the number of cubs in the flock will be relatively small, and there may even be no cubs."
According to the statistics of Hoh Xil Management Office of Yangtze River Source Park of Sanjiangyuan National Park Administration, the number of Tibetan antelopes has been increasing year by year. In 2019, the number of Tibetan antelopes was 4,860, an increase of 338 compared with 2018.
Lian Xinming said: "It is expected that the migration of Tibetan antelopes will end in early September this year, and the number of Tibetan antelopes is still expected to continue to increase."
Tibetan antelope is a national first-class protected animal.
At the end of May every year, Tibetan antelopes from Sanjiangyuan in Qinghai, Qiangtang in Tibet and Altun Mountain in Xinjiang all go to Zhuonaihu Tibetan Antelope Aggregation in the hinterland of Hoh Xil to give birth to lambs.
Wu Xiaomin, an expert on Tibetan antelope protection in China and a researcher at Shaanxi Institute of Zoology (Northwest Institute of Endangered Animals), said: "The migration of Tibetan antelopes is a process in which female Tibetan antelopes return to their habitats one after another after giving birth. At first, the returning group that left the litter place was relatively large, but then the Tibetan antelopes will return to their respective habitats along different paths according to different geographical populations. "
In order to ensure the safe relocation of Tibetan antelopes, the reporter learned that the Hoh Xil Management Office of Yangtze River Source Park of Sanjiangyuan National Park Administration has arranged staff to continuously carry out video surveillance and patrol in the main relocation areas.
If it is found that Tibetan antelopes try to cross the highway, the mountain patrol team will carry out temporary traffic control at the first time, so that the flocks can safely pass through the wildlife passage, and ensure that they are as little disturbed by human beings as possible during the migration.
So, how to get rid of the summer heat in daily life?
Experts suggest that when going out in summer, try to avoid the high temperature period, and it is best not to walk or work in the hot sun around noon, because the sunshine is the strongest in this period, and the possibility of heatstroke is higher.
If you have to go out at this time, you must do a good job of protection, such as wearing a parasol, sun hat and sunglasses. If you have the conditions, it is best to apply sunscreen to prevent sunburn.
Try to choose light-colored, breathable cotton, hemp and silk fabrics, and wear less chemical fiber clothing, so as to avoid heat stroke caused by excessive sweating.
In hot and sultry weather, prepare plenty of water to drink in time, and don't wait for thirst to drink water, because once you feel thirsty, your body is already short of water, so drink 150 ml to 200 ml each time, and drink warm boiled water instead of ice water.
According to the temperature, the average person drinks 1.5 liters to 2 liters of water every day, and the high-temperature workers drink 3 liters to 5 liters of water every day.
When sweating more, you can supplement some salt water appropriately to make up for the salt lost by sweating.
In addition, the human body is prone to potassium deficiency in summer, which makes people feel tired and fatigued. Potassium-containing tea is an excellent summer drink.
Eat more fruits and vegetables with high water content in summer, such as lettuce, cucumber and tomatoes; Fresh fruits, such as peaches, apricots, watermelons, melons, etc., have a water content of 80% to 90%, which can be used to supplement water; Dairy products can not only replenish water, but also meet the nutritional needs of the body.
In addition, people working in high temperature environment should properly supplement drinks containing potassium, magnesium and other elements.
Summer is long and the night is short, the temperature is high, the metabolism of the human body is vigorous, the consumption is large, and it is easy to feel tired.
Adequate sleep can relax brain and body systems, which is beneficial to work and study, and is also a measure to prevent heatstroke.
Experts say that the best time to go to bed is from 22: 00 to 23: 00 and the best time to get up is from 5: 30 to 6: 30.
Be careful not to lie under the air conditioner outlet and electric fan when sleeping, so as not to suffer from air conditioning diseases and hot cold.
Experts suggest that people who are outdoors or working at high temperature can carry heatstroke prevention drugs such as ten drops of water, Rendan, Huoxiang Zhengqi Water or Huoxiang Zhengqi Pill with them, or put them in the nearest workplace and use them at any time to prevent heatstroke.
