Is it reasonable for a 3-year-old child to sue the school after he has been smashed in the university playground?
2020-07-26 05:01:11 Source: Legal Daily Author: Wang Sishuo Editor: Wang Sishuo
The playground was smashed, and the children were compensated and then appealed to the school
□ Correspondent of this newspaper Zhao Yifan
When 3-year-old Xiaowen was playing in a university playground, he was accidentally shot in the head by Chen Mou of softball team.
After Chen Mou paid compensation, Xiaowen's father, Mr. Wen, as Xiaowen's legal representative, sued the school to the court, demanding the school where the playground happened to apologize, and paying a total of 20,000 yuan for medical expenses and mental damages.
Recently, after hearing the case, Haidian District People's Court of Beijing held that the school had set up a protective net in the playground at the time of the incident, and had fulfilled its proper security obligation, and that Chen Mou had already made compensation, so it ruled that the plaintiff's claim was rejected.
Mr. Wen claimed that during the summer vacation in 2019, he took Xiaowen to play in the school playground, when the softball team was training in the playground.
In order to avoid the risks, Xiaowen, Mr. Wen and many other children and parents are active in the safe areas designated by softball teams.
However, Chen Mou, a softball team member, dropped the ball when he threw the ball, causing the softball to fly over the protective net to the above-mentioned safe area and hit Xiaowen's back.
Mr Wen immediately took Xiaowen to the hospital for treatment and was diagnosed as head injury.
According to Mr Wen, the facilities of the school stadium do not meet the relevant safety regulations, and the team and related facilities are not effectively managed.
The school's fault led to the above incidents, which caused Xiaowen to suffer great pain physically and mentally, and also brought great pain to his family, and the school should bear legal responsibility for this.
In this regard, the school argued that the school had set up a protective net in the playground, and posted management regulations and training notices, telling that entering the playground must keep a safe distance from the training ground and remind people to pay attention to their own safety. The plaintiff could not prove that the school "failed to fulfill its security obligations", so it did not agree to compensation.
After hearing the case, the court held that the place where the incident occurred was a place open to the public free of charge by the university involved in the case. Although the school has the obligation of security for the management of the playground, this obligation of security only needs to meet the general duty of care.
At the time of the incident, the school set up a protective net in the playground, which has fulfilled its proper security obligations. In addition, Chen Mou also compensated Xiaowen for medical expenses, transportation expenses and other losses of more than 2,000 yuan according to the compensation agreement reached before, and both parties agreed to solve the dispute once.
Afterwards, Xiaowen's parents once again advocated school compensation, which was unfounded in law. The court ruled that all the plaintiff's applications were rejected.
After the verdict was pronounced, neither party appealed, and the verdict is now in effect.
According to Article 37 of China's Tort Liability Law, schools, as managers of public places, have the obligation of security; In the case that the third person's behavior causes damage to others, the third person bears tort liability, while the public place manager who fails to fulfill the security obligation should bear corresponding supplementary liability.
According to the judge, as the manager of public places, he is most likely to know the actual situation of the whole place, foresee the possible dangers and damages, and thus most likely to take necessary measures to prevent the occurrence of losses or reduce the degree of damages, and the cost of avoiding and reducing damages is the lowest, so the law stipulates that he shall bear the corresponding guarantee obligations for engaging in social activities.
In this case, for unspecified people entering the playground which is open to the public free of charge, the school's security obligation should be adapted to the social activities it engages in. Specifically, it should mainly take basic security measures and have the obligation to inform hidden dangers.
In judicial practice, it is not appropriate to impose excessive security obligations on managers of public places.
If the school has set up a protective net and fulfilled its obligation of informing, it can be concluded that the school is not at fault and should not bear legal responsibility.
In addition, even if the managers of public places such as schools fail to fulfill their security obligations, their responsibilities are also a supplement to damages. According to the newly promulgated Civil Code, managers can also claim compensation from the third party after taking supplementary responsibilities.
Therefore, in such accidents, the victim should not expand the scope of claims after receiving compensation from the direct infringer.
