Israel has strengthened its repeated prevention and control of the epidemic
At the early stage of Covid-19 outbreak, Israeli prevention and control measures have achieved remarkable results.
However, with the gradual lifting of the ban on prevention and control measures, the number of confirmed cases of Covid-19 in Israel has increased obviously recently, and the Israeli government has taken urgent measures to strengthen the prevention and control of the epidemic.
On February 28th, the first case of Covid-19 was confirmed in Israel, so that all entry and exit ports were quickly closed, non-essential industries were suspended, schools were taught online, public transportation and non-essential social activities were restricted, cities with severe epidemics were blocked, and military and police jointly maintained prevention and control measures.
This series of measures quickly achieved positive results. By mid-May, the number of newly confirmed Covid-19 cases in Israel once fell back to single digits.
With the epidemic under control, all Israeli prevention and control measures were completely unsealed. Since June, the number of newly diagnosed cases in Covid-19 has gradually rebounded.
Especially after entering July, the epidemic spread rapidly.
In recent days, there are more than 1,500 new cases in Israel every day for eight days, and as of July 25, the number of new cases reached 916 on that day.
As of July 25th, there were 59,745 confirmed cases and 448 deaths in Israel.
Facing the rapid rebound of the epidemic, the Israeli government has taken urgent measures to strengthen the prevention and control of the epidemic.
On July 6th, after the number of confirmed cases exceeded 30,000, the Israeli government closed gymnasiums, swimming pools, bars, nightclubs and other public entertainment places, and introduced a policy of restricting public transportation, stipulating that the maximum number of passengers on each bus should not exceed 20.
On the 17th, the Israeli government announced a series of new restrictive measures, including the implementation of "city closure" on weekends, which stipulated that "city closure" should be implemented from 17: 00 every Friday to 5: 00 every Sunday.
During this period, people can go out, but shops, shopping centers, barbershops, beauty salons, libraries, zoos, museums, exhibition halls, swimming pools and tourist attractions will be closed, while supermarkets, pharmacies and other basic service places will remain open.
At the same time, gatherings of more than 10 people are prohibited on all dates and time periods, gymnasiums, studios and other places will be closed, restaurants and cafes are prohibited from having meals, and only take-out services are allowed.
At the same time, the Israeli people did not pay enough attention to the severity of the epidemic and failed to form a joint force with the government in fighting the epidemic.
After repeated outbreaks in Israel, many people took to the streets to protest and March because the government's prevention and control measures affected their own economic interests.
On July 11th, tens of thousands of people held demonstrations in Tel Aviv, arguing that the anti-epidemic policy affected the economy.
On the evening of the 21st, thousands of protesters gathered in front of Prime Minister Netanyahu's residence in Jerusalem to protest against Prime Minister Netanyahu's promulgation of prevention and control measures against restaurants and coffee halls without giving corresponding compensation.
In addition, many people do not abide by the regulations of wearing masks and keeping a safe social distance of two meters when they are outdoors. In order to avoid being fined by the police for not wearing masks, many people only wear masks on their chin or hang them on their wrists.
During the repeated outbreaks, schools were the hardest hit areas in Covid-19. According to a reporter's recent visit to this kindergarten, teachers and students in the kindergarten did not wear masks as required by the government, and did not keep a safe social distance of two meters from each other, which laid a hidden danger for a large number of teachers and students to be infected with viruses.
Professor Elie Wachsman, a member of the expert advisory group of Israel's National Security Council against the epidemic, thinks that Israel is moving towards a "dangerous situation", pointing out that the epidemic prevention and control measures taken by Israel at present are not enough, and all leisure and entertainment venues and summer schools should be closed to control the further spread of the epidemic.
Wachsman said that Israel lacks an overall plan to fight the epidemic, and the parliament and government departments should abandon their respective interests as soon as possible, reach an agreement on fighting the epidemic, and formulate clear steps including relevant restrictive measures in different departments.
