Which way to use in colleges and universities will be specified in the Admissions Charter.
However, there are also some colleges whose admission principle is to give priority to the total score, and there is no grade difference between majors.
That is to say, the candidates in the admission range will be queued according to the total score. When the score does not reach the first professional volunteer admission score line, it will be seen whether it has reached the second professional volunteer admission score line, and so on until the last professional volunteer is admitted. There is no grade difference between professional volunteers.
The so-called "professional grade difference" means that when colleges and universities arrange candidates' majors, they determine the admission majors of candidates who choose to apply for different majors according to one or several score values published in the enrollment charter. This score value is called "professional grade difference".
That is, the difference in scores between the first professional volunteers and the non-first professional volunteers in colleges and universities, and the differential scores among the professional volunteers, such as 3 points, 2 points, 1 point, etc.
For example.
Let's say that Xiao Ming, a student, applied for college A and scored 560 points. His professional volunteers are: computer, international trade, automation, mechanical engineering and e-commerce. The professional admission of college A adopts the method of professional grade difference. The grade difference is divided into 2 points, 1 point, 1 point and 0 point.
In the professional assignment, if Xiaoming's first professional volunteer meets the professional admission requirements and the professional has a planned balance, then Xiaoming is admitted to the "computer" major; If the computer is not accepted, his score will be deducted by 2 points, and the candidates who apply for "international trade" with the first major will be sorted according to the score of 558 points to determine whether they meet the professional admission conditions; If it is still not satisfied, the score will be deducted by 1 point (ie 557 points) for the admission of the third professional volunteer "automation"; If it is still unsatisfied, the score will be deducted by one point (i.e., 556 points) for admission to the fourth major. If the follow-up major still fails to meet its professional aspirations, it will not be deducted any more, and so on.
Different universities have different professional level differences
With the popularization of parallel volunteer, many colleges and universities have abolished the professional grade difference, but some colleges and universities still retain this method this year. According to the Admissions Charter published by each school, more than 20 universities have set up professional grade difference this year.
For example, Sichuan Agricultural University, Shandong University of Science and Technology, Heilongjiang University of Traditional Chinese Medicine, Jiangsu University of Science and Technology, Jiangxi Normal University, Chengdu Medical College, northeast dianli university, Jimei University, Nanjing Medical University, Nanjing University of Technology, Ningxia University, Shandong University of Technology, China Civil Aviation Flight Academy, etc.
Among these universities, each university has different professional levels.
Some colleges and universities have grade differences in each major, such as Ningxia University, where candidates whose files have been put into the school are admitted according to the order in which candidates fill in their professional volunteers.
However, some universities have different professional grades between different majors.
Jimei University, for example, has a total score of 4 points, that is, the difference between the first professional volunteer and other professional volunteers is 3 points, and there is no difference between other professional volunteers, which is regarded as parallel volunteer, while the difference between other professional volunteers and adjustment professional volunteers is 1 point.
When filling in their volunteers, candidates and parents must carefully read the admission policies of the schools reported to see if there is any professional grade difference, and what is the form of the grade difference. While giving full consideration to the scores, they should also reasonably analyze the schools and majors to be selected. If the colleges and universities explicitly adopt the grade difference method for admission in the enrollment charter, candidates should pay attention to the gradients among the majors when choosing majors to improve their admission chances.
